Fig. 1A and B showed the typical SEM images of as-prepared OMCP nanospheres. Uniform nanospheres with an average diameter of 550–650nm were clearly observed in Fig. 1A. The high magnification SEM image (Fig. 1B) further demonstrated the nanospheres had smooth surface and relatively uniform size. Fig. 1C showed particle size distribution of OMCP, demonstrating the diameter of OMCP was 400–800nm, and mainly concentrated in 550–650nm. Fig. 1D showed UV–vis absorption and PL emission spectra of OMCP. In the UV–vis absorption (blue line), we could see that it had typical UV–vis absorption peaks. The absorption peak at approximately 430nm could be due to the n–π* transition of N in aromatic ring. Moreover, the absorption peak at approximately 360nm demonstrated the n–π* transition of amino-groups in conjugate structure [35,36]. The excitation wavelength (λex
) and emission wavelengths (λem
) of OMCP were 356nm, 460nm from PL spectra of OMCP, respectively. The FT-IR spectrum of OMCP, oPD and mPD were shown in Fig. 1E. The adsorption peaks at 3321, 3240 and 3210cm−1 correspond to the N–H stretching mode, implying the presence of secondary amino groups. The peaks at 1601 and 1536cm−1 were assigned to C–N and C–C stretching vibrations in phenazine structure, respectively. The peaks at 1239 and 1370cm−1 were associated with the C–N stretching in the benzenoid and quinoid imine units [37]. The peaks at 900 and 830cm−1 could be attributed to theout-of-plane deformation of C–H on a 1, 2, 4-tetrasubstituded ben-zene ring, implying the polymer has the basic phenazine skeleton. Moreover, the peaks at 754 and 593cm−1 were characteristic of C–H out-of-plane bending vibrations of benzene nuclei in thephenazine skeleton [38]. The composition of the OMCP was confirmed by EDS spectrum in Fig. 1F. The inset showed the concentrations corresponding to C, N and O elements.
